text_blocks.snippet: There are multiple matches for cascarilla, including a plant and a white eggshell powder used in spiritual practices:

list.title: Plant
list.snippet: Cascarilla is the aromatic bark of the West Indian shrub Croton eluteria, which is native to the Caribbean and has been naturalized in other tropical regions. The word "cascarilla" comes from Spanish and is a diminutive of cáscara. Cascarilla has been used for making incense and as a tonic. In the past, it was also added to tobacco before smoking because of its pleasant odor.

list.title: White eggshell powder
list.snippet: Cascarilla is also a white eggshell powder used in spiritual practices. It's used in rituals of different religions, including Santeria, Voodoo, Palo Mayombe, Espiritismo, and Ifa. Some uses for cascarilla include:
Dissolving it in water for baths to remove negative energy
Spreading it on the body or around the home
Using it as chalk to draw sigils and circles of protection
Dusting oneself with it or making the sign of the cross on the body
Protecting against psychic attacks and "energy vampires"
Keeping away negative spirits, ghosts, and demons

answer_box.snippet: Cascarilla is a plant. In the past, cascarilla was added to tobacco before smoking because it has a pleasant odor when burned. The bark is used as medicine. People use cascarilla for digestion problems, diarrhea, and vomiting, but there is no good scientific evidence to support these uses.
